Time Series Analysis on US Monthly Unemployment Rate

Abstract

Although the unemployment rate in the United States has remained relatively stable over the years, there are many recent advancements that have the potential to adversely affect it such as layoff spillover, AI, and market re-correction. This report seeks to conduct a time series analysis on monthly unemployment rates in the United States and build a SARIMA model to make further predictions. We will go about this using the Box-Jenkins approach: plotting the time series data, transforming, identifying dependence orders, estimating parameters, diagnostics, and selecting an appropriate model. In order to strengthen the model and identify trends, we will utilize unit root testing and spectral analysis. This analysis includes time series plots, ACF/PACF plots, ADF tests, STLs, Shapiro-Wilk tests, periodograms, and forecasting. At the end of this report, we will explore and compare four eligible SARIMA models to determine the best-performing one and utilize it to make a next-year prediction.

2. Data

The data was taken from the Kaggle dataset, US Monthly Unemployment Rate [https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tunguz/us-monthly-unemployment-rate-1948-present/data] by user Bojan Tunguz. The data was collected by the US Bureau of Labor Statistics and was collected through the Current Population Survey. It contains monthly unemployment rates ranging between January 1948 and December 2019. The values represent the proportion of unemployed persons in the labor force (%) and are non-negative. The sample size is 864.

As mentioned in the introduction, I chose this data set because of its personal resonance. This dataset is importantand useful to studybecause it allows us to analyze trends, compute future predictions, and contribute to a well-informed society.

3. Methodology

3.1 SARIMA

We will be applying the Box-Jenkins method which uses the AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) models to determine the best fit of a time-series model to past values of a time series. However, we will be modifying this slightly to use the SARIMA model instead, where the S stands for Seasonal. ARIMA and SARIMA are both algorithms for forecast, taking into account past values (autoregressive, moving average) and predicts future values based on that. However, SARIMA takes into account any seasonality patterns and introduces seasonality as a parameter, thus extending its capabilities and potentially increasing accuracy. There are six steps to fitting models to time series data according to the Box-Jenkins method. These steps involve:

Step 1: Plotting the data

As with any data analysis, we should begin by constructing a time plot of the data and inspect the graph for any anomalies.

Step 2: Transforming

If we notice any anomalies upon inspection, applying a transformation of the data may prove useful. For example, if the variability in the data increases with time, then it will be necessary to transform the data to stabilize the variance and improve the normal approximation. In such cases, root, log, or Box-Cox power transforms can be employed.

Step 3: Identifying dependence orders

After appropriately transforming the data, we should identify the preliminary values: \(p\) (autoregressive order), \(d\) (order of differencing), and \(q\) (moving average order). Usually, a time plot of the data will indicate if any differencing is required. If it is, then we will difference the data once, \(d=1\), and inspect the time plot of \(\triangledown x_t\). If further differencing is necessary, then we can difference the data again, \(d=2\), and inspect the time plot of \(\triangledown^2 x_t\). However, we must be careful not to overdifference the data otherwise dependence might be introduced where none exists. In addition to time plots, assessing the ACF can also indicate whether or not differencing is necessary.

Step 4: Estimating parameters

We must find apporpriate parameters for the SARIMA model: SARIMA\((p,d,q) \times (P,D,Q)_{S}\). We can estimate the parameters by analyzing the sample ACF and PACF plots. If we transform or difference the time series (which we do), we examine those ACF/PACF plots to determine the parameters of the non-seasonal and seasonal components of the SARIMA model.

Step 5: Diagnostics

A complete diagnosis includes:

  • plotting the time series of the standard residuals,

  • plotting the estimated ACF of the standardized residuals,

  • plotting the normal Q-Q plot of the standardized residuals, and finally

  • plotting the p values for the Ljung-Box statistic and determining whether the Q-statistic is significant or not

Step 6: Model selection

Finally, to select the best performing model, we compare the AIC, AICc, and the BIC across all models. Lower values are ideal.

3.2: Unit Root Testing

Unit root tests determines whether a time series is non-stationary and possesses a unit root. After defining a test statistic or significance level, we can either accept or reject the null hypothesis. The null hypothesis is that the a unit root exists and the alternative hypothesis implies stationarity, trend stationarity, or explosive root depending on the test that is applied.

In this case, we will be applying the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test. The null hypothesis is that the data are non-stationary and the alternative hypothesis is that the data are stationary. We set the significance level = 0.01 to provide higher confidence in concluding stationarity. If the p-value is less than or equal to the significance level, we reject the null hypothesis. If the p-value is greater than the significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. We can also define a critical value according to the Dickey-Fuller \(t\)-distribution to test our hypothesis. The ADF statistic is a negative number where the more negative it is, the stronger the rejection of the hypothesis that there is a unit root at some level of confidence.

3.3: Spectral Analysis

Spectral analysis is a powerful technique used in time series analysis to examine the underlying structure of the data by analyzing its frequency components. We can identify periodic patterns or repeated cycles, particularly through the mvspec function. It is used to estimate the spectral density using kernel smoothing. We will use the Daniell Kernel as our pre-defined kernel parameter, a simple moving average kernel. The kernel smoothing helps in reducing the variance of the periodogram estimates, making the spectral density estimates more reliable.

4. Results
Figure 1: Time Series Plot of Original Data Figure 2: ACF and PACF of Original Data

Upon visual inspection of the time series plot of the original data [Figure 1], there appears to be seasonal pattern suggesting that the data is not stationary. To be sure that our visual analysis is correct, we perform the Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) Test to check for stationary. The ADF test produces a p-value of 0.02362 which is greater than our significance level of 0.01 so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the data are non-stationary, as we presumed in our visual inspection.

To double check our assumption that there is a seasonal component, we will perform a Seasonal decomposition of Time series by Less (STL) which breaks up the time series into seasonal, trend, and irregular components.

Figure 3: Decomposition of Original Data

After analyzing the graphs, there is a strong, apparent seasonal component and a perhaps a slight cyclical trend. The remainder appears to be random with no distinct pattern. To test for normality, we perform the Shapiro-Wilk Test. With significance level 0.01, the p-value of the Shapiro-Wilk tests yields a value less than 0.01 thus we can conclude that the sample data does not come from a population that is normally distributed.

Since we have identified that the data is not normal, we want to transform the data to stabilize the variance and improve the normal approximation. The slowly decaying ACF and PACF \(\phi_{1,1} \approx 1\) of the original data [Figure 2] also suggests us to take the log. In this analysis, we will be applying a log transformation since our data is strictly positive.
Figure 4: Periodogram of Original Data Figure 5: Periodogram of Log Transformed Data

We conduct spectral analysis to identify any significant periodic components on the original data and the transformed data. In the periodogram of the original time series data [Figure 4], there does not appear to be any significant peaksor any peaks for that matter. The log periodogram [Figure 5] does not indicate any significant peaks either but there is a slight wave-like pattern with dips at each integer value, suggesting a lower frequency. This lower frequency indicates an annual cycle.
Figure 6: Time Series Plot of Non-Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data Figure 7: ACF and PACF of Non-Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data
Figure 8: Time Series Plot of Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data Figure 9: ACF and PACF of Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data

Since we have also identified that the data is not stationary and contains seasonality and trends we want to difference the transformed data. Upon visual inspection of Figure 6, differencing the transformed time series makes the graph appear much more stationary. To double check, we conduct the ADF test for stationarity. The p-value yields a value less than the significance level, 0.01, so we can conclude that the transformed data with difference, \(d\), equal to 1 is stationary and we do not need to differentiate again.

We need to find the values \(p\), \(d\), \(q\), \(P\), \(D\), \(Q\), and \(S\) for our SARIMA model. First, we will work with the non-seasonal parameters of the SARIMA model, namely, \(p\), \(d\), and \(q\). We have established that \(d=1\). To determine \(p\) and \(q\), we will refer to the ACF/PACF plots [Figure 7] of our differenced and transformed data. In both plots, its not clear whether they are tailing off or cutting off, which is where ARMA comes in. We will test out a few p and q combinations. To get a \(p\) value for AR for ARMA model, we will look at the PACF plots for spikes. The most prominent spikes are at 2 and 3. Thus its AR(2) and AR(3). To get a \(q\) value, we will look at the ACF plot. The most prominent spike is at a value of 2. Thus its MA(2). So for the non-seasonal parameters, we will try (2,1,2) and (3,1,2).

Now lets identify the seasonal parameters. The data is on a monthly level so \(S=12\). There is an indication that seasonality exists, mostly by looking at the decomposed stacked plots [Figure 3] with data, seasonality, trend, and difference. Since the series has a stable seasonal pattern over time, \(D=1\). Looking at the ACF/PACF plots [Figure 9] for the seasonally differenced data, we see that the ACF tails off and the PACF cuts off after 1, indicating AR(1). So we will set the seasonal parameters (1, 1, 0). However, we will also try (0, 0, 0) assuming no seasonality as well.
Figure 10: Model 1 Diagnostics Figure 11: Model 2 Diagnostics
Figure 12: Model 3 Diagnostics Figure 13: Model 4 Diagnostics

For the SARIMA\((2,1,2) \times (1,1,0)_{12}\) model [Figure 10], there is no obvious patterns in the standard residuals plot but there are some outliers exceeding 2 standard deviations in magnitude. The plot of the estimated ACF of the residuals shows no apparent departure from model assumptions except a significant lag value of 2. The normal Q-Q plot of the residuals show that the assumption of normality is reasonable, although there are some outliers. Many of the Q-statistics are statistically significant. The AIC, AICc, and BIC values are -3.271947, -3.271863, and -3.238451, respectively.

For the SARIMA\((2,1,2) \times (0,0,0)_{12}\) model [Figure 11], there is no obvious patterns in the standard residuals plot but there are some outliers exceeding 2 standard deviations in magnitude. The plot of the estimated ACF of the residuals shows no apparent departure from model assumptions except a significant lag value of 1. The normal Q-Q plot of the residuals show that the assumption of normality is reasonable, although there are some outliers. Many of the Q-statistics are statistically significant, but not as many compared to the other models. The AIC, AICc, and BIC values are -3.790915, -3.790834, and -3.757788, respectively.

For the SARIMA\((3,1,2) \times (1,1,0)_{12}\) model [Figure 12], there is no obvious patterns in the standard residuals plot but there are some outliers exceeding 2 standard deviations in magnitude. The plot of the estimated ACF of the residuals shows no apparent departure from model assumptions except a significant lag value of 2. The normal Q-Q plot of the residuals show that the assumption of normality is reasonable, although there are some outliers. Many of the Q-statistics are statistically significant. The AIC, AICc, and BIC values are -3.269863, -3.269745, and -3.230784, respectively.

For the SARIMA\((3,1,2) \times (0,0,0)_{12}\) model [Figure 13], there is no obvious patterns in the standard residuals plot but there are some outliers exceeding 2 standard deviations in magnitude. The plot of the estimated ACF of the residuals shows no apparent departure from model assumptions. The normal Q-Q plot of the residuals show that the assumption of normality is reasonable, although there are some outliers. Many of the Q-statistics are statistically significant. The AIC, AICc, and BIC values are -3.770012, -3.769898, and -3.731364, respectively.

All of these models are valid, however, the best-performing model is: SARIMA\((2,1,2) \times (0,0,0)_{12}\) because it has the lowest AIC, AICc, and BIC across all models with values -3.790915, -3.790834, and -3.757788, respectively.
Figure 14: Next Year Forecast Figure 15: Forecast Values

Looking at the forecast plot [Figure 14] and forecast values [Figure 15] suggests that the US unemployment rate will maintain stability over the next 12 months/1 year, showing minimal fluctuations or unexpected changes.

Conclusion and Future Study

In conclusion, applying the methods unit root testing and spectral analysis proved useful in creating an optimal model of SARIMA\((3,1,2) \times (0,0,0)_{12}\) to predict a year-long forecast of unemployment rates in the United States by month. The forecast indicates that the unemployment rate will remain relatively stable in the next year, namely, without any unexpected jumps or dips.

In our analysis, we started by plotting our original time series along with its ACF and PACF. Through visual inspection, ACF/PACF tests, and the Shaprio Wilk test, we determined that the original time series was not normal and had a lot of variance, which prompted us to apply a log transformation of the data. We also discovered that the data is not stationary and contains seasonality and trends through visual inspection, ADF tests, and spectral analysis. To resolve this, we differenced the transformed data, repeated the ADF test to ensure stationarity, and identified \(d=1\).

We used the log and differenced ACF and PACF to determine our non-seasonal parameters for the SARIMA model, where we identified AR(2), AR(3), and MA(2) and chose to test (2, 1, 2) and (3, 1, 2). We then used the decomposed plot and seasonal log and differenced ACF and PACF plots to determine our seasonal parameters, where we identified AR(1) and chose to test (1, 1, 0) and (0, 0, 0) to see how our model would perform assuming no seasonality.

From there, we explored combinations of the non-seasonal and seasonal parameters with \(S=12\) for monthly data to create four SARIMA models. We performed diagnostics on each model and determined that all of the models were acceptableno obvious patterns in the standard residual plots, no apparent departure from model assumptions in the ACF of residuals plot, and the assumption of normality is reasonable in the normal Q-Q plot of the residuals. However, many of the Q-statistics were statistically significant according to the Ljung-Box plot but the second model did not have as many significant Q-statistics (higher p-value) suggesting that the residuals resemble white noise and implies that the model is more adequate. We found that SARIMA\((3,1,2) \times (0,0,0)_{12}\) performed best with the lowest AIC, AICc, and BIC. We then used this model to form our next year prediction.

If given more time, I would have applied more methods to further enhance my model and explored other models besides SARIMA, such as state space models, to potentially find a better performing model. I also would have liked to conduct more Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to get a better understanding of the data itself and identify any interesting patterns. I believe that introducing other variables into the equation could produce insightful correlations and help determine the cause of unemployment in the United States. Adding predictor variables would allow me to perform machine learning with the US unemployment rate as the response variable and explore other models that way.

Overall, we successfully employed all the steps of the Box-Jenkins method and applied various methods to create a SARIMA model to form valuable insights about the future monthly US unemployment rate through forecasting. I have gained a wealth of knowledge from this project and throughout the course, which I will carry forward in my data science journey.

Appendix

library(astsa)
library(forecast)
library(tseries)
library(xts)
data <- read.csv("~/pstat 174/USUnemployment.csv")
head(data)
data <- xts(data[,-1], order.by = as.Date(data[,1]))
unemployment <- as.vector(t(data))
unemployment <- ts(unemployment, start = c(1948,1), frequency = 12)
plot.ts(unemployment, ylab = "US Unemployment Rate (%)", main = "Time Series Plot of Original Data")

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(unemployment)
pacf(unemployment)
adf.test(unemployment, alternative = "stationary")
decomposed <- stl(unemployment, s.window = "periodic")
plot(decomposed)
residuals <- decomposed$time.series[,"remainder"]
shapiro_test <- shapiro.test(residuals)
shapiro_test
log_unemp <- log(unemployment)
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
mvspec(unemployment, taper=.1, log="no")
k = kernel("modified.daniell", c(3,3))
mvspec(unemployment, kernel=k, taper=.1, log="no")

par(mfrow=c(2,1))
mvspec(unemployment, taper=.1, log="yes")
mvspec(unemployment, kernel=k, taper=.1, log="yes")
# Non-seasonal
diff_log_unemp <- diff(log_unemp)
plot(diff_log_unemp, main = "Time Series Plot of Non-Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data")

# Seasonal 
diff_log_unemp_s <- diff(log_unemp, 12)
plot(diff_log_unemp_s, main = "Time Series Plot of Seasonal Transformed and Differenced Data")

# Non-seasonal
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(diff_log_unemp)
pacf(diff_log_unemp)

# Seasonal
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(diff_log_unemp_s)
pacf(diff_log_unemp_s)
adf_test <- adf.test(diff_log_unemp, alternative = "stationary")
adf_test
sarima(diff_log_unemp, 2, 1, 2, 1, 1, 0, 12) # -3.271947
sarima(diff_log_unemp, 2, 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, 12) # -3.790915
sarima(diff_log_unemp, 3, 1, 2, 1, 1, 0, 12) # -3.269863
sarima(diff_log_unemp, 3, 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, 12) # -3.770012
sarima.for(diff_log_unemp, 12, 2,0,2,2,0,0, 12, main = "Forecast for 2020")
